  "context_summary": "19-year-old college student presents with four days of worsening sore throat, now severe and localized to the right side, after being told two days ago it was likely strep and starting antibiotics with little improvement. His voice sounds muffled to the intake nurse. The doctor has not yet examined the oropharynx and is deciding whether this is still simple tonsillitis/pharyngitis or has progressed to a peritonsillar abscess needing drainage.",
  "good_next_question": "Can you open your mouth all the way for me right now, and are you able to swallow your own spit normally, or has your voice sounded muffled, like you're talking with something in your mouth?",
  "rationale": "Trismus, pooling saliva or drooling, and a muffled 'hot potato' voice form the clinical triad that reliably separates peritonsillar abscess from simple tonsillitis, because these findings reflect a deep space infection with mass effect pushing on the pterygoid muscles and soft palate, beyond what tonsillar inflammation alone produces. Even severe tonsillitis usually still allows full mouth opening and normal swallowing of saliva. Detecting trismus or drooling here is urgent because PTA requires needle aspiration or incision and drainage plus antibiotics, and delay risks airway compromise or spread into deep neck spaces. Asking about pain severity alone is a weaker discriminator since both conditions cause severe throat pain; this question isolates the specific findings tied to abscess formation and changes management immediately.",
  "tags": [
    "ent",
    "peritonsillar_abscess",
    "pta",
    "tonsillitis",
    "adolescent",
    "sore_throat"
  ],
